+++ read...
When light falls on one side of a plant, auxin moves to the shaded side.
The shaded side, having more auxin, undergoes faster cell elongation.
The lighted side elongates more slowly because it has less auxin.
This unequal growth causes the stem to curve toward the light.
Thus, bending occurs due to differential growth controlled by auxin distribution.
