<sn><md>### Commonly Used Auxins

* IAA (indoleacetic acid)
* IBA (indolebutyric acid)
* NAA (naphthaleneacetic acid)
* 2,4-D (Dichloro Phenoxy Acetic Acid)
* NOA (Naphthoxy Acitic Acid)

The `2,4-D` is used for ++callus induction++ whereas the <br> `other auxins` are used for ++root induction++.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Function of Auxins

| **Function Category**                                | **Details**                                                                                           |
| ---------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Cell Enlargement**                                 | **Shoot Growth** : <br>Internodes<br>Tubers<br>Bulbs                                                               |
| **Root Growth**                                      | Storage Roots<br>Adventicious Roots                                                                     |
| **Fruit Growth**                                     | Strawberry – Receptacle enlargement                                                                   |
| **Rooting of Cuttings**                              | Propagation;<br> Greenhouse and Nursery Crops:<br> Hormodin, Rootone, etc.; Commercial preps of 2,4-D         |
| **Apical Dominance**                                 | **Auxin:Cytokinin Ratio**<br> High – Dormant Axillary Buds;<br> Low – Axillary Bud Growth                       |
| **Herbicide**                                        | **High Concentration 2,4-D**<br>Dicots more sensitive<br>Monocots less sensitive<br>Weed control in cereal crop |
| **Prevent Abscission of Leaves, Flowers and Fruits** | Older leaves; Ripe Fruit                                                                              |
| **Tissue Culture Propagation (Differentiate Organ)** | **Auxin:Cytokinin Ratio**<br>High – Roots<br>Low – Shoots<br>Equal – Callus                                    |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Additional Response

* Differentiate sensitivity of developing fruit
* Direction of growth (tropism of stems or roots)
* Parthenocarpy in some plants
* Enlargement and cell division of callus tissue culture
* Flower initiation and development
* Sex determination
* Fruit set, growth and development</md></sn>